John Edward: Linguistic skills, essential for global citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a record of academic excellence, and this continued in 2018 with another set of exceptional results for examinations, which is supported by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other community efforts.
With over 30,000 students in Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Independent Schools Council (SCIS), are trying to provide services at the highest level for their students and parents.
Independent schools propose to prepare their students for high school and higher education, their chosen career and their place as global citizens.
As an educational sector that can design and implement a special school curriculum, we note that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela said: "If you speak to a man in a language he understands, your words will reach his mind.
If you speak to him in his own language, words will reach his heart."
This is a strong reminder that we cannot rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust people from other countries.
Based on the recent results of this year's competition, we note that foreign languages are at the top of the classes, with the highest promotion rates in independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who have studied foreign languages have obtained a Higher Grade A certificate.
Data collected from 74 SCIS school members showed that 72% of students obtained a Higher Grade A certificate in Mandarin; 72% of those who study German, 69% of those who study French and 63% of those who study Spanish obtained such a certificate.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will certainly need in the future.
Now, foreign languages, such as matter, are held in the same way as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in independent school curricula and in other fields.
A survey carried out by the British Commission for Employment and Skills in 2014 found that for the reasons why employers gave them to fight for job vacancies, 17% had been attributed to a lack of linguistic skills.
As a result, more and more language skills become imperative for young people to prepare for their future career.
With more opportunities for jobs that require foreign languages, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of the career that someone chooses, if they have learned a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future, having such a ability throughout their lives.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically put a multilingual person before the competition.
According to a survey by YouTube on over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% could not speak a foreign language well enough to carry on a conversation, and the French language was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
Therefore, investment in learning foreign languages is important for children today.
With more languages, especially in developing countries, children will have greater opportunities to find significant jobs.
In Scotland, each school will teach other foreign languages.
A number of schools will focus on more modern classical languages, while others will learn languages that are considered to be the most important for the United Kingdom when they look forward to 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be more languages of choice in independent schools, with teaching frameworks that are specialized in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and encourage them with the skills necessary to succeed, no matter what the future may be.
It cannot at this point be denied, in a global business environment, that languages continue to be vital for the future of the country, so that this must be reflected in education.
Indeed, modern languages should really be considered "international communication skills".
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence for young people in Scotland.
It's a good thing to do.
